frameDefinitions: An Entity aids in the successful completion of a Purpose.
This frame concerns an Evaluee being judged for its quality, i.e. how much it would probably be liked.
This Frame is concerned with evaluating an Evaluee as being suitable for a Purpose or a User, presupposing some choice that is being made about which Evaluee to use for the Purpose or User.
A certain Idiosyncrasy belongs to an Entity distinguishing it from other entities.
An Object with an understood function is or is not in a state ready to perform that function.
frameExamples: A box is an <t>ideal</t> storage device.
(1) We need to build more houses <t>suitable</t> for local residents.
If you have 32 totally <t>idiosyncratic</t> meanings for a term in a class, everyone will be very confused when they talk! DNI
listRoleDefinitions: The item which is useful for some purpose.
The kind of task which is promoted by the use or presence of the <fen>Entity</fen>.
When the <fen>Entity</fen> is useful for a <fen>Purpose</fen>.
The <fen>Evaluee</fen> is being judged for its quality.
This Frame Element marks constituents expressing the entity that is judged to be more or less suitable for some <fen>Purpose</fen> or <fen>User</fen>.
This Frame Element marks constituents that express the <fen>Purpose</fen> for which the <fen>Evaluee</fen> is judged to be suitable or unsuitable.
This role marks expressions that indicate a <fen>User</fen> to whom
An entity or characteristic  belonging to the <fen>Entity</fen>.
The <fen>Entity</fen> that has a certain distinguishing <fen>Idiosyncrasy</fen>.
The entity with an understood purpose.
listRoleExamples: Being a project leader is not a job for which <fex>everybody</fex> is suited.
We need to plan more buildings suitable <fex>for disabled people</fex>.
Paul has an idiosyncratic <fex>tendency to go barefoot at all times</fex>.
